[[File:Brooklyn Museum - The Healing of Ten Lepers (Guérison de dix lépreux) - James Tissot - overall.jpg|thumb|300px|[[James Tissot]] - The Healing of Ten Lepers (Guérison de dix lépreux) - [[Brooklyn Museum]]]] Jesus' '''cleansing of ten lepers''' is one of the [[Miracles of Jesus in the Gospels|miracles of Jesus]] reported in the [[Gospels]] ([[Gospel of Luke]] 17:11-19).<ref>''Bible Knowledge Background Commentary: Matthew-Luke'' by David C. Cook and Craig A. Evans (Feb 27, 2003) {{ISBN|0781438683}} page 365</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Lk.%2017:11-19&version=TNIV |title=Biblegateway Luke 17:11-19 |publisher=Biblegateway.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-18}}</ref>
According to [[Luke the Evangelist|Luke's]] account, on his way to [[Jerusalem]], [[Jesus]] encountered ten lepers. He healed them, but only one returned to thank Jesus afterward.
According to Berard Marthaler and [[Herbert Lockyer]], this miracle emphasizes the importance of faith, for Jesus did not say: "My power has saved you" but attributed the healing to the faith of the beneficiaries.<ref>Berard L. Marthaler 2007 ''The Creed: The Apostolic Faith in Contemporary Theology'' {{ISBN|0-89622-537-2}} page 220</ref><ref>Lockyer, Herbert, 1988 ''All the Miracles of the Bible'' {{ISBN|0-310-28101-6}} page 235</ref>
