'''Irreligion in the [[United Arab Emirates]]''' is rare, with only up to 4% of people [[Irreligion by country|reporting irreligious beliefs]] according to a Gallup poll. It is illegal for Muslims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewire.com/global/2013/12/13-countries-where-atheism-punishable-death/355961/|title=There Are 13 Countries Where Atheism Is Punishable by Death|author=AbOhlheiser|date=|work=The Wire}}</ref> with [[apostates]] from Islam facing a maximum sentence of the [[Capital punishment in the United Arab Emirates|death penalty]] under [[Blasphemy law in the United Arab Emirates|the country's anti-blasphemy law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freethoughtreport.com/map/|title=Freedom of Thought Report - Map|author=|date=|work=freethoughtreport.com}}</ref> As such, there have been questions regarding [[freedom of religion in the United Arab Emirates]].

Atheism in the region is mainly present among foreign [[Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates|expatriates]] and a very small number of local youth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/is-gulf-youth-increasingly-drawn-to-atheism|title=Is Gulf youth increasingly drawn to atheism?|work=The National|date=19 August 2012|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-bab.com/blog/2013/august/email-from-an-arab-atheist-2.htm|title=Email from an Arab atheist|work=Al-Bab|date=11 August 2013|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> According to [[Sultan Sooud Al-Qassemi]], due to Islam being founded in the [[Arabian Peninsula]] over 1,400 years ago, the [[Persian Gulf]] region enjoys a long Islamic history and tradition, and it is strongly associated with national identity; thus, any distancing or criticism of religion "equates to distancing oneself from national identity".<ref name="AM"/> Al-Qassemi notes that the use of [[social media]] via the internet remains the strongest medium of expression for Gulf atheists, while providing anonymity; a pioneering Gulf blogger is the Emirati atheist Ahmed Ben Kerishan, who is known in the [[Blogging in Arab countries|Arabic blogosphere]] for advocating atheist and secular views.<ref name="AM">{{cite news|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/gulf-atheism-uae-islam-religion.html|title=Gulf atheism in the age of social media|work=[[Al-Monitor]]|accessdate=11 July 2015|first=Sultan Sooud|last=Al-Qassemi|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710191405/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/gulf-atheism-uae-islam-religion.html|archivedate=10 July 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/3643/-pioneer-bloggers-in-the-gulf-arab-states|title=Pioneer Bloggers in the Gulf Arab States|work=Jadaliyya|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=11 July 2015|first=Sultan Sooud|last=Al-Qassemi}}</ref>

