{{Orphan|date=October 2017}}

'''Teyolía''' was an animic entity of the human being resided physically located in the heart according to the cosmovision of the [[Aztec|ancient Aztecs]] and in the beliefs of some modern indigenous groups from Mexico and Central America.

Together with the ''tonalli'' and the ''ihíyotl'' was one of the three strengths that brings life and health to the humans. It was the part of the human being considered as the one that trascended to [[afterlife]] to different realms according ones way of death. After the [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire|Spanish conquest]] the term was assumed by Spaniard translators as equal to the word «ánima» and «alma» (soul),{{sfn|López Austin|2012a|pp=253}} which have some reminiscences in current expressions among modern indigenous.<ref name="olson">{{Cite book|last= Olson|first = Richard G.|title = Technology and Science in Ancient Civilizations|publisher= Praeger|location= Santa Barbara, California|year= 2010|url = https://www.questia.com/read/124045386/technology-and-science-in-ancient-civilizations||subscription= y}}</ref>

== Etymology ==
The [[nahuatl]] word ''teyolía'' incorporates the [[prefix]]  «te-» and the substantive «yolía». The particle «te-» is an indefinite pronominal [[prefix]] that indicates possession, so when it is placed before a noun it can be translated as «of somebody, of another, of the people, of some».<ref>{{Cite book|url = http://www.historicas.unam.mx/publicaciones/publicadigital/libros/gramatica/cgn_002.pdf|title = Compendio de la gramática náhuatl|author = Sullivan, Thelma D.|publisher= Instituto de Investigaciones Históricas. UNAM|year= 2014|edition= 4th.|isbn = 9786070254598|page= 55}}</ref> The noun «yolía» contains the [[Root (linguistics)|root]] «''yol''» meaning «life», consequently it can be translated as «''that what makes to live''».{{sfn|López Austin|2012a|p=254}} All together the word teyolía might be translated as «what makes to live the people». It is related etymologically with the word «yollotl», used to describe the heart.{{sfn|López Austin|2012b|p=222}}

== Description ==
According to the Aztec thought the ''teyolía'' was an animic entity that gives life to the human beings located in the heart and, therefore, inside every person's chest. Related with the half part of the cosmos.<ref name="olson" /> In addition to the vitality it was attributed it to be the source of knowledge, tendency, affections, passions, memory and will.<ref name="Fitzsimmons">{{Cite book|author= Fitzsimmons, James L.|title= Death and the Classic Maya Kings|location= Austin, Texas|publisher= University of Texas Press|year= 2009|page= 42|url = https://www.questia.com/read/120781924/death-and-the-classic-maya-kings|subscription = y}}</ref>{{sfn|López Austin|2012a|pp=254-255}}

The Aztecs believed that after dead the teyolía was the part of the man that separated from the body remained immortal. The teyolía remained some days on the surface of earth be carried afterwards to one of any different destinations in which the Aztecs believed. The final destination of the teyolía was determined by every person's way of dead.<ref name="Fitzsimmons" /><ref>{{cite journal|year= 2013|title= La muerte entre los mexicas. Expresión particular de una realidad universal|work= Arqueología Mexicana. Edición especial: La muerte en México. De la época prehispánica a la actualidad.|volume= |issue= 52 |page= 18|location= México|publisher= Raíces|issn= 0188-8218|url= }}</ref> The teyolía of the warriors, for example, was carried to the sun realm (''nepantla tonatiuh'') where they turned into beautiful birds.

Among the modern indigenous peoples the term is used  in some deformed ways as «yolía», «yolo», «teyolotl», «I:l», «yuhlu», «I:ll(or)»; or, by means of Spanish terms «alma», «ánima» or «espíritu».<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.medicinatradicionalmexicana.unam.mx/termino.php?l=1&id=139|title= yolo|website= Diccionario Enciclopédico de la Medicina Tradicional Mexicana|author= UNAM|location= México|access-date= December 4, 2015|year= 2009}}</ref>

